  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Children and Youth Education Response Activity CYERA</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">(Democratic Republic of the Congo):  Due to existing crises 3.5 million Congolese primary school children are not in school. Adolescent girls in conflict and displaced settings are especially at risk of sexual and gender-based violence, which often leads to drop out and further vulnerability. To address these challenges, TBD Children and Youth Education Response Activity (CYERA) will increase children&apos;s access to education, create safer learning environments, and improve the quality of teaching and learning in schools. CYERA will target children and youth (both girls and boys) living in crisis- and conflict-affected communities of Ituri, North Kivu, and South Kivu. CYERA is designed to deliver rapid education services in other provinces (e.g., Haut Uele, Tanganyika, Kasa&amp;iuml; Central) if and when requested based on anticipated needs. Equal access to quality education can create pathways for greater economic growth, improved health outcomes, sustained democratic governance, and more peaceful and resilient societies. CYERA will build the resilience of Congolese children and youth so they propel the DRC on its own journey to self- reliance. Additionally, FY 2020 resources will be provided as grants to local organizations focused on child protection and education. These grants will help a new set of domestic implementing partners develop their technical and administrative capacity to deliver such programs in the future without an international intermediary. .CYERA will advance CDCS DO 2 by strengthening education services delivery, increasing access to education services, and improving collaboration between education actors. CYERA will also contribute to TO 3 by strengthening individual and community resilience through education, by strengthening the institutional resilience of local actors, and by restoring services for crisis- and conflict-affected populations, including those impacted by COVID and Ebola... ........</narrative>
  </description>
